      <div id ="topBar"><p class="quadrit" id = "volumeText">Enter "X" to Randomize the Output of a Cell!</p></div>
      <div id ="volBar"><p id = "volumeText">Volume inputs are randomized by default. They are used to shape the
      amplitude envelope of an instrument, which makes a randomized list of volume settings particularly good at adding character
      to an otherwise flat lead.</p></div>
      <div id ="tspBar"><p id = "volumeText">Transpose inputs are not randomized by default. Their values are used to shift
      the pitch of an instrument by the set number of semitones. Entering an invalid hex input in any cell will produce
      a randomized value, which can be useful when the pulse channel is being used for rhythmic, atmospheric, and all around
      non-tonal sound.</p></div>
      <div id ="cmdBar"><p id = "volumeText">Command inputs change the shape of a sound in a variety of ways, depending
      on the command. Valid keys are: "C", "E", "H", "K", "L", "M", "P", "R", "S", and "V". Inputting an invalid key will
      generate a randomly selected valid command. These values are not randomized by default.</p></div>
      <div id ="prmBar"><p id = "volumeText">Command parameters shape one of two things: how the command executes, or the
      extent to which it is executed. For every command processed by the table, a random command parameter will be assigned in output
      (assuming you do not enter one yourself). These values are not randomized by default. </p></div>
      <div id ="cmdTwoBar"><p id = "volumeText">Command(2) inputs change the shape of a sound in a variety of ways, depending
